39:49.820 --> 39:59.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now special
correspondent Charlayne
Hunter-Gault has a story on how
a once-segregated

39:59.430 --> 40:03.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pocket of a small Southern town
is making
a comeback.

40:03.334 --> 40:05.369 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of our Race Matters
series.

40:05.403 --> 40:10.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: The
city's historic
African-American business
district, known

40:10.307 --> 40:15.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as the Hot Corner, helped foster
commerce
in a place once steeped in
segregation.

40:15.813 --> 40:22.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Athens native Homer Wilson, who
owns a popular
barbershop, explains how the Hot
Corner developed

40:23.020 --> 40:24.855 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the Jim Crow era.

40:24.889 --> 40:30.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HOMER WILSON, Owner, Wilson's
Styling Shop:
It was all-black from -- we call
it the bottom,

40:30.828 --> 40:32.797 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
all the way down.

40:32.830 --> 40:34.698 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're just black business.

40:34.732 --> 40:37.568 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: What
type of businesses?

40:37.601 --> 40:42.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HOMER WILSON: Funeral home
businesses, dentists,
lawyers, motels, you name it.

40:42.907 --> 40:46.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: That was
essential
for the black community, which
had few other

40:46.744 --> 40:51.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
choices and could not use the
then white-only
businesses uptown.

40:51.248 --> 40:55.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fifty-six years ago, when I was
one of first
two black students at the
University of Georgia,

40:55.920 --> 40:59.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I couldn't come into Athens and
go to a movie
theater like this.

40:59.490 --> 41:05.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I couldn't even take bowling
because the bowling
alley was here, and it was
segregated.

41:05.196 --> 41:10.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But after flourishing, many Hot
Corner businesses
moved to malls farther out
during the '70s

41:10.734 --> 41:12.603 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
or died.

41:12.636 --> 41:17.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Homer Wilson held on to his
family's property,
home to Wilson's Soul Food, for
three decades.

41:17.741 --> 41:18.709 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And then:

41:18.742 --> 41:21.078 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is your place here?

41:21.111 --> 41:26.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Forty-one-year-old David Eduardo
came knocking,
in search of a place to rent for
his restaurant

41:26.484 --> 41:28.552 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he calls The World Famous.

41:28.586 --> 41:32.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID EDUARDO, Owner, The World
Famous: The
Hot Corner is a great place to
do business.

41:33.023 --> 41:34.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: What
drew you to it?

41:34.959 --> 41:38.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID EDUARDO: The fact that
there was a restaurant
there before that had a strong
30-plus-year

41:38.996 --> 41:41.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
run of success was very
encouraging.

41:41.699 --> 41:46.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They a had great reputation, and
we could
only hope to be half as
successful as they

41:46.971 --> 41:48.205 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
were.

41:48.239 --> 41:49.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: So, you
went to Mr.
Wilson and said?

41:49.840 --> 41:52.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID EDUARDO: And begged him
for the opportunity
to open up shop next door.

41:52.343 --> 41:55.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: And what
did you think
about that, Mr. Wilson, the
white boy coming

41:55.145 --> 41:56.280 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in?

41:56.313 --> 42:00.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HOMER WILSON: Well, you know, he
wasn't the
first one.

42:00.251 --> 42:02.086 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

42:02.119 --> 42:08.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HOMER WILSON: So, we had a lot
of great chances
to rent it to a lot of people,
but David was

42:08.259 --> 42:09.593 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
more persistent.

42:09.627 --> 42:12.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID EDUARDO: The fact that it
is so coveted
is not lost on me.

42:12.496 --> 42:17.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know that with that space
comes tremendous
responsibility and history.

42:17.334 --> 42:21.605 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we have to be good stewards
for the community.

42:21.639 --> 42:25.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm very, very happy that the
Wilson family
gave us the green light.

42:25.476 --> 42:30.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: A green
light to gentrification,
a turnoff to those who helped
build this area,

42:30.881 --> 42:33.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but the spreading of the welcome
mat to people
from new communities.

42:33.984 --> 42:38.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID EDUARDO: We have cuisine
from everywhere
around the world, our live
entertainment.

42:38.088 --> 42:42.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On any given night, you can find
hip-hop,
comedy, singer-songwriters.

42:42.259 --> 42:45.129 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We want to be a place for
everyone, not just
anyone.

42:45.162 --> 42:52.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HOMER WILSON: This end of town
is coming back
to where it used to be, where we
had all this

42:52.102 --> 42:54.705 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that would go on, on our corner.

42:54.738 --> 42:59.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Both men
agree the
Hot Corner, rich in history,
good and bad,

42:59.577 --> 43:01.378 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is a special pace.

43:01.412 --> 43:06.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HOMER WILSON: There is a spirit
that hovers
over this place makes things,
people mix and

43:06.984 --> 43:11.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mingle different down here than
they do other
places.

43:11.255 --> 43:24.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This togetherness, it can work
if we can learn
to supply the right information
to people.

43:24.535 --> 43:26.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Like
what?

43:26.704 --> 43:32.476 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HOMER WILSON: It's all right to
be white.

43:32.509 --> 43:34.311 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's all right to be black.

43:34.345 --> 43:35.312 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

43:35.346 --> 43:36.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID EDUARDO: Amen.

43:36.680 --> 43:39.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I would encourage folks to just
get out of
their comfort zone.

43:39.984 --> 43:46.490 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Folks from all cultural
backgrounds, gender,
socioeconomic classes, they
gravitate to this

43:46.523 --> 43:47.491 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
side of town.

43:47.524 --> 43:49.693 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's a very welcoming
environment, I think.

43:49.727 --> 43:53.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Where
once people
were kept from mixing, now the
Hot Corner

43:53.897 --> 43:56.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
has become a hot spot for all.

43:56.367 --> 44:04.975 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
In Athens, Georgia, I'm
Charlayne Hunter-Gault
for the "PBS NewsHour."

44:05.009 --> 44:15.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A question that
has been raised
here: Why aren't more men going
into fields

44:15.819 --> 44:17.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
dominated by women?

44:17.788 --> 44:22.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Stigma is a big part of the
answer, our economics
correspondent, Paul Solman,
reported last

44:22.826 --> 44:24.028 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
week.

44:24.061 --> 44:28.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, he focuses on one man
many might
want to emulate.

44:28.065 --> 44:30.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of our weekly series
Making Sense.

44:30.034 --> 44:32.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON, Elementary
School Teacher:
We already got a man outside,
and I need you

44:32.436 --> 44:34.338 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be outside, especially at
will linebacker.

44:34.371 --> 44:39.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Harold Johnson
coaches linebackers
for the Ridge View Blazers in
Columbia, South

44:39.543 --> 44:42.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Carolina, where high school
football is a
rite of masculine passage.

44:42.746 --> 44:46.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMOS MYLES, Football Coach: You
start getting
tired, then you start getting
lazy in your

44:46.650 --> 44:47.618 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
mind-set.

44:47.651 --> 44:48.619 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Now, hey, you can't think.

44:48.652 --> 44:50.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You have to be focused.

44:50.688 --> 44:53.090 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have to get control of your
breathing.

44:53.123 --> 44:55.893 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Amos Myles is the
bad cop.

44:55.926 --> 44:58.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But Harold Johnson isn't exactly
the good
one.

44:58.295 --> 44:59.396 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: Downhill first.

44:59.430 --> 45:00.764 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We don't ever attack lateral.

45:00.798 --> 45:01.765 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're playing linebacker.

45:01.799 --> 45:03.434 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Downhill first.

45:03.467 --> 45:06.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Pretty much every
high school
football coach is a guy, of
course.

45:06.036 --> 45:10.107 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And men are no rarity in
secondary school
classrooms either.

45:10.140 --> 45:15.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGELA BAUM, Educator: It's
about 40 percent
of male teachers at high school
level.

45:15.612 --> 45:21.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But in elementary
school, says
educator Angela Baum, the
percentage is minuscule.

45:21.085 --> 45:25.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGELA BAUM: So, between 1
percent and 5 percent
of early childhood teachers are
male.

45:25.489 --> 45:29.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Do you guys like
having a man
for your teacher?

45:29.693 --> 45:31.462 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENTS: Yes!

45:31.495 --> 45:36.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Their teacher is
Harold Johnson,
the linebacker coach, whose main
job turns

45:36.633 --> 45:42.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out to be running this second
grade classroom,
after six years teaching
kindergarten.

45:42.039 --> 45:47.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Early education teacher is a job
for which,
given the labor market for men,
especially

45:47.745 --> 45:52.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the South, qualified guys
would be hired
right away.

45:52.382 --> 45:55.119 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Harold Johnson has taken
advantage ever since
college.

45:55.152 --> 45:57.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: I just decided I
wanted to
be an early childhood major.

45:57.688 --> 46:02.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Smart move, he
learned, as good
male gigs were proving ever
harder to come

46:02.226 --> 46:04.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by in the wake of the crash of
'08.

46:04.061 --> 46:08.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: The dean of the
colleges came
in to just greet all the
freshmen and stuff,

46:08.499 --> 46:10.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and he kind of walked in, and he
looked around,
and he was giving his speech.

46:10.801 --> 46:12.503 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He just stopped me.

46:12.536 --> 46:13.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His speech was like, hey that
guy right there
is going to get a job before all
you all.

46:13.103 --> 46:14.071 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And so I just laughed.

46:14.104 --> 46:15.973 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I'm looking round, like, me?

46:16.006 --> 46:18.675 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he was just like, yes, it's
you.

46:18.709 --> 46:24.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But eight years
later, coach
Johnson still has surprisingly
scant competition,

46:24.715 --> 46:27.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when he attends yearly childhood
conferences,
for example.

46:27.584 --> 46:30.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: Everybody
looking like, hey
what you doing here?

46:30.420 --> 46:32.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, this isn't P.E. or
anything.

46:32.422 --> 46:34.792 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I'm just like, I know.

46:34.825 --> 46:37.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's reading and how to teach
kids how to
read.

46:37.194 --> 46:38.529 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's what I'm here for, to
learn that.

46:38.562 --> 46:39.730 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
So...

46:39.763 --> 46:41.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And then they get
embarrassed,
I assume?

46:41.431 --> 46:43.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: Yes, there's
somewhat of embarrassment
and somewhat of intrigue.

46:43.500 --> 46:46.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're like, what made you want
to do that,
or like, what made you want to
teach?

46:46.904 --> 46:48.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Same thing that made you want to
teach.

46:48.472 --> 46:50.307 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Like, you enjoy it.

46:50.340 --> 46:53.010 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Especially when I was a
kindergarten teacher,
it was definitely like, nobody
could believe

46:53.043 --> 46:54.378 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

46:54.411 --> 46:58.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was just like a, ahhh, kind
of sympathetic
kind of situation.

46:58.115 --> 46:59.316 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Oh, aren't you
sweet?

46:59.349 --> 47:00.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: Yes, aren't you
sweet?

47:00.584 --> 47:03.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: So is there
something different
about him?

47:03.187 --> 47:08.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, he's patient, more patient
than fellow
coach Amos Myles perhaps.

47:08.325 --> 47:11.795 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But even the ever so macho Myles
says:

47:11.829 --> 47:13.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AMOS MYLES: I think patience is
key.

47:14.031 --> 47:16.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With that, you have to have
patience with
kids.

47:16.400 --> 47:18.135 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It doesn't matter what level
you're on.

47:18.168 --> 47:21.405 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STUDENT: I really love my
country.

47:21.438 --> 47:26.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: First of all,
what was happening?

47:26.810 --> 47:28.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Before we even got to the
passage, what was
happening?

47:28.712 --> 47:32.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: You don't think
there's a difference
in the patience required to be a
kindergarten

47:32.216 --> 47:34.451 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
teacher, as opposed to, say, a
TV journalist?

47:34.484 --> 47:35.452 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

47:35.485 --> 47:36.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: I personally
don't.

47:36.920 --> 47:39.323 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just feel like you got the
patience for
what you got patience for.

47:39.356 --> 47:41.458 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You hold them to a high
standard, then they
will perform.

47:41.491 --> 47:43.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A lot of times, it's like, oh,
they're only
5, they're only 5.

47:43.493 --> 47:46.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, that's why you don't have
patience for
them, because you treat them
like they're

47:46.129 --> 47:47.931 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
only 5.

47:47.965 --> 47:49.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you treat them like, no,
you're 5, you're
not 4 anymore, you know how to
do this, then

47:49.666 --> 47:51.034 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you get a better result.

47:51.068 --> 47:53.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think it's just -- the mind
frame of
going into it is one thing.

47:53.136 --> 47:56.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People say patience, but I think
it's not
really patience.

47:56.707 --> 47:59.142 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Just, you got to teach what you
want to happen.

47:59.176 --> 48:02.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So what Johnson
seems to have
is a different mind frame.

48:02.946 --> 48:06.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: I feel like that
one thing
people just having the wrong
impression.

48:06.516 --> 48:10.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just, oh, they're little kids,
they're dirty,
they got snot hanging out, they
don't know

48:10.988 --> 48:13.090 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how to tie their shoes, they
always ask for
something, always whining.

48:13.123 --> 48:16.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I always tell them, OK, I'm
pretty sure
you have got a co-worker there
always asking

48:16.693 --> 48:20.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you for stuff, that's always
aggravating,
that always, maybe not being
dirty, might

48:20.197 --> 48:21.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have snot running out their nose
too.

48:21.565 --> 48:23.467 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She was too smart at that
school.

48:23.500 --> 48:25.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She don't have any way to help
her.

48:25.235 --> 48:29.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: In fact, what
struck me after
spending a day with Harold
Johnson is that,

48:29.206 --> 48:35.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
while he's exceptional at his
job, he's much
like the best side of any of us,
and his gender

48:35.145 --> 48:37.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is a help, not a hindrance.

48:37.347 --> 48:43.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STUDENT: Boy teachers are more
nice, and they
understand more, and they're not
as mean as

48:43.654 --> 48:44.621 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
girl teachers.

48:44.655 --> 48:46.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STUDENT: Yes, exactly.

48:46.223 --> 48:50.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: They understand you
better because
you're a boy and they're men?

48:50.193 --> 48:51.161 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: Yes.

48:51.194 --> 48:52.429 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: Yes.

48:52.462 --> 48:55.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Now, girls, in my
experience,
are lots of fun.

48:55.899 --> 48:57.401 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, I have two daughters.

48:57.434 --> 48:59.236 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're a lot of fun.

48:59.269 --> 49:05.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So why is the boy teacher more
fun than the
girl teacher?

49:05.108 --> 49:09.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STUDENT: Because boys do more
awesome stuff
than girls.

49:09.546 --> 49:11.281 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: No!

49:11.315 --> 49:17.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: On behalf of you
girls, I do
not think boys do more awesome
stuff than

49:17.554 --> 49:19.323 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
girls.

49:19.356 --> 49:22.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But educator Angela Baum says
male teachers
do bring something different to
the table,

49:22.492 --> 49:24.361 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or to the floor.

49:24.394 --> 49:30.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGELA BAUM: Some experts
suggest that perhaps
men play with children
differently than women

49:30.334 --> 49:31.868 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
do.

49:31.902 --> 49:34.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, men may be more likely to
engage in what
we call rough-and-tumble play.

49:34.237 --> 49:38.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's that vigorous chasing,
wrestling kind
of play.

49:38.675 --> 49:41.878 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's good for young
children, both young
boys and young girls.

49:41.912 --> 49:46.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: There's one last
aspect of Johnson's
teaching worth mentioning,
especially for

49:46.650 --> 49:48.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a Making Sense segment.

49:48.752 --> 49:54.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He teaches economics to second
graders, including
lessons in managing a work
force.

49:54.524 --> 49:59.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HAROLD JOHNSON: We did supply
and demand,
and then we talked about wants
and needs.

49:59.463 --> 50:02.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We brought the materials to make
something,
so they had instructions.

50:02.332 --> 50:07.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So one was a sugar cookie, one
was some cocoa
mix, one was a winter mix.

50:07.204 --> 50:09.006 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so they had a factory
assembly line.

50:09.039 --> 50:10.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, somebody got behind.

50:10.841 --> 50:13.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, you know, the people at
the front
was finished, the people at the
back were

50:13.810 --> 50:16.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
overworked, and the person in
the middle was
kind of slowing down.

50:16.480 --> 50:18.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So the people at the end, they
were like,
well, can we get some help?

50:18.115 --> 50:19.349 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was like, no, they finished
their job.

50:19.383 --> 50:21.084 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, then they really got
frustrated with the
middle people.

50:21.118 --> 50:22.519 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I asked them, well, how did that
feel?

50:22.552 --> 50:23.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they was like, man, that's
hard work.

50:23.553 --> 50:24.821 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's a lot of pressure on
you.

50:24.855 --> 50:26.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I was like, and imagine, you
all was making
sugar cookies.

50:26.757 --> 50:29.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Imagine if you really was doing
something,
building a car or something.

50:29.426 --> 50:31.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, we talked about that.

50:31.294 --> 50:35.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: OK, one last
question for those
men out there who might possibly
be considering

50:35.265 --> 50:36.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
if this job is for you.

50:36.933 --> 50:38.468 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How gratifying is this work?

50:38.502 --> 50:40.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
HAROLD JOHNSON: Oh,
tremendously.

50:40.437 --> 50:45.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the thing that I enjoy
the most is
when you see a kid have the aha
moment or

50:45.442 --> 50:47.778 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
either change their whole
perception of something.

50:47.811 --> 50:54.718 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, I have seen boys who hated
reading are
running to go read first.

50:54.751 --> 50:57.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so it's just like, man, you
know, I had
something to do with that.

50:57.554 --> 51:02.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Or if I can take this 180 days
and make a
lifetime of difference, then
that's all worth

51:02.492 --> 51:03.527 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

51:03.560 --> 51:05.362 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's all worth it for me.

51:05.395 --> 51:08.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: For the "PBS
NewsHour" at Lake
Carolina Elementary School in
Blythewood,

51:08.999 --> 51:15.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
South Carolina, I'm economics
correspondent
Paul Solman.

51:15.572 --> 51:20.844 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Brief But Spectacular

51:20.877 --> 51:27.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to another in
our Brief
But Spectacular series.

51:27.584 --> 51:30.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from Michael
Eric Dyson.

51:30.387 --> 51:36.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He teaches at Georgetown and is
the author
of "Tears We Cannot Stop: A
Sermon to White

51:36.827 --> 51:38.595 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
America."

51:38.628 --> 51:40.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL ERIC DYSON, Author,
"Tears We Cannot
Stop: A Sermon to White
America": One of the

51:40.397 --> 51:43.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
greatest privileges of being
white in this
country is to encounter a police
person on

51:43.366 --> 51:50.974 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the street and live to tell
about it.

51:51.007 --> 51:55.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When many people say, let's get
rid of political
correctness, that's a shorthand
for, let me

51:55.178 --> 51:57.747 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
keep on being bigoted the way I
was before.

51:57.781 --> 52:03.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As the great philosopher Shawn
Carter said,
you was who you was before you
got here, player,

52:03.453 --> 52:06.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and you might change, but that's
just the
top layer.

52:06.323 --> 52:10.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you think about want
collective white
fragility of many white
Americans, you know,

52:10.560 --> 52:12.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
black people, brown people, red,
yellow people,
you know what we do?

52:12.329 --> 52:15.632 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm going to break a secret to
you.

52:15.665 --> 52:19.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're very cautious and careful
about how
you might interpret things,
because you're

52:19.870 --> 52:20.837 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
very fragile.

52:20.871 --> 52:22.038 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Your feelings might get hurt.

52:22.072 --> 52:25.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You have had 44 of 45
presidents.

52:25.609 --> 52:29.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Most CEOs of American Fortune
500 companies
have been white.

52:29.279 --> 52:31.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Where are the tears of white
America coming
from?

52:31.648 --> 52:34.751 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To be white is to be seen as,
I'm just a human
being.

52:34.784 --> 52:36.086 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm just an American.

52:36.119 --> 52:37.621 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why can't you guys do the same?

52:37.654 --> 52:41.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, many white brothers and
sisters don't
understand they possess a race.

52:41.057 --> 52:42.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When you hear gender, what do we
think?

52:42.726 --> 52:44.227 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Oh, that must be the women.

52:44.261 --> 52:46.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We don't think, hey, I possess a
masculinity.

52:46.296 --> 52:49.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And, often, it's a toxic
masculinity.

52:49.266 --> 52:53.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many white brothers and sisters,
when they
hear the issue of race, they
think the other.

52:53.370 --> 52:55.038 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They never think themselves.

52:55.071 --> 52:59.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was the great, late Gore
Vidal who said,
we live in the United States of
amnesia.

52:59.309 --> 53:01.978 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, America is obsessed with
history when,
what?

53:02.012 --> 53:06.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a reenactment of the Civil
War, some
battle that was lost in the
South.

53:06.416 --> 53:09.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But when it's about black
history, why don't
you people get over that?

53:09.486 --> 53:11.188 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Stop obsessing about slavery.

53:11.221 --> 53:13.323 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Stop talking about reparations.

53:13.356 --> 53:15.625 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Stop speaking about historical
repression.

53:15.659 --> 53:17.227 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Talk about what's going on now.

53:17.260 --> 53:20.063 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When it makes America look
great, claps, applause.

53:20.096 --> 53:22.999 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When it doesn't, get out of my
face.

53:23.033 --> 53:24.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Stop living in the past.

53:24.401 --> 53:27.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
My role is, for many
communities, a paid pest.

53:27.871 --> 53:28.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's what I do.

53:28.872 --> 53:30.106 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm a professor.

53:30.140 --> 53:32.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I get paid to think about
stuff that is
pestiferous.

53:32.042 --> 53:33.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I try to use humor.

53:33.410 --> 53:37.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I try to use self-deprecation,
but the ultimate
goal is the same.

53:37.080 --> 53:42.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can we challenge the forces of
unconscious
white privilege and implicit
bias to come

53:42.319 --> 53:45.222 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
out of the closet and to be held
accountable?

53:45.255 --> 53:47.023 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's my job.

53:47.057 --> 53:51.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of my white students, after
reading a
book that horrendously detailed
the tragedies

53:51.928 --> 53:57.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and horrors of white violence
against black
people, said, "For the first
time in my life,

53:57.234 --> 53:59.135 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I feel ashamed to be white."

53:59.169 --> 54:04.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I didn't want him to get stuck
in a pocket
of misery and guilt, because
white guilt ultimately

54:04.708 --> 54:06.076 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
will not fix anything.

54:06.109 --> 54:08.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're going to get into circles
that I will
never get into.

54:08.178 --> 54:10.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You're going to go home to
Thanksgiving.

54:10.113 --> 54:15.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Go home and talk to granny, not
before you
eat the turkey or the stuffing
or the pumpkin

54:15.118 --> 54:16.886 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
pie.

54:16.920 --> 54:19.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But after, then say to her, you
know what,
I have got black and brown and
red and yellow

54:20.023 --> 54:21.391 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
friends, and it's not what you
say.

54:21.424 --> 54:24.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Or say to your cousin and your
uncle, this
is not how it goes down.

54:24.094 --> 54:28.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when we do that, we can get
rid of the
amnesia that has blocked a white
grappling

54:28.665 --> 54:33.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with its own problems and
issues, and tell
the truth about race in America.

54:33.737 --> 54:35.472 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
My name is Michael Eric Dyson.

54:35.505 --> 54:39.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And this is my Brief But
Spectacular challenge
to white America.

